  <h2>About the System Itself</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>What system type does my site actually support, and why?</strong> The soil drives this,
      and it shapes the whole project. If a provider hasn't evaluated the soil, ask how their
      recommendation accounts for it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>How is the system sized for my household?</strong> The system should match the home's
      expected use, not a generic default.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>What happens if the soil evaluation calls for a different design?</strong> This is the
      question that prevents the biggest surprises — knowing in advance how a bid changes if the ground
      requires an alternative system.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>About the Scope and Timeline</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>What exactly does this project include — and what would be extra?</strong> Design, approvals, access work, and property restoration should all be spelled out.</li>
    <li><strong>What's the expected timeline and sequence?</strong> Understand the stages and roughly how long each takes, weather permitting.</li>
    <li><strong>How will access and restoration be handled?</strong> Especially important on rural or wooded lots where reaching the work area is involved.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>About Approvals</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>What approvals apply, and who handles them?</strong> Often the installer coordinates approvals, but confirm it. Requirements vary by county — see <a href="/tennessee-septic-permits-and-approvals/">Tennessee septic permits and approvals</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>About the Long Term</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Where will the tank and field be placed, and how accessible will they be for service?</strong> A field you can reach is cheaper to maintain for decades.</li>
    <li><strong>What maintenance will this system need?</strong> Especially relevant for alternative systems with additional components.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Scope Beats Price</h2>
  <p>
    The thread running through all of these is scope. Two bids that look different on price often differ
    because they assume different systems or include different work — a point our guide on
    <a href="/new-septic-installation-cost-factors/">installation cost factors</a> explains. Asking
    these questions turns three confusing quotes into a fair comparison, and it tells you a lot about
    which provider communicates clearly. When you're ready to start the conversation,
    <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> and bring these questions along.
  </p>
